<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><TEI:TEI xmlns:TEI="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><TEI:teiHeader/><TEI:text><TEI:body><body xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><div id="d39873e70"><div id="d39873e1793"><note id="d39873e34955" place="end"><ab id="d39873e34956"><foreign xml:lang="it"><hi rend="underline">Specchio mistico</hi><note id="d39873e34960" place="inline"><hi rend="underline">sepolcrale</hi></note>
    
                                                                                 = Patera etrusca.-</foreign><lb id="d39873e34964" n="1"/></ab></note><note id="d39873e34965" place="end"><ab id="d39873e34966"><foreign xml:lang="it">Che cosa scorgiamo noi d'entro lo specchio? la vuota immagine, la larva dell'uomo.</foreign><lb id="d39873e34969" n="2"/></ab></note><note id="d39873e34970" place="end"><ab id="d39873e34971"><foreign xml:lang="it"><add>Dunque</add> Lo specchio è il simbolo naturale dell'<hi rend="underline">ombra</hi>, dei <hi rend="underline">Dii manes</hi>, del <hi rend="underline">corpo<lb id="d39873e34984" n="3"/>
                    disanimato</hi>. Dunque è buon arnese allegorico pel sepolcro, analogo<lb id="d39873e34987" n="4"/>
                    alla moschera che pur veggiamo scolpita su molte urne.</foreign><lb id="d39873e34989" n="5"/></ab></note><note id="d39873e34990" place="end"><ab id="d39873e34991"><foreign xml:lang="it">La parte lucida <add>e convessa</add> era rappresentativa di specchio, l'altra parte (con-<lb id="d39873e34997" n="6"/>
                    cava e fornita d'un orlo o labbro rilevato) formava un genere parti-<lb id="d39873e34999" n="7"/>
                    colare di patina o patera, adoperata nei riti sepolcrali</foreign><lb id="d39873e35001" n="8"/></ab></note><note id="d39873e35002" place="end"><ab id="d39873e35003"><foreign xml:lang="it">Eca Suthines: Eca Suthineisl: Eca Suthinesl pan.<lb id="d39873e35006" n="9"/><hi rend="underline">Suthina</hi> è come dire in latino <hi rend="underline">sospes</hi>, <hi rend="underline">incolumis</hi>.</foreign><lb id="d39873e35016" n="10"/></ab></note><note id="d39873e35017" place="end"><ab id="d39873e35018"><foreign xml:lang="en">In the Religion itself of the Etruscans, as far as it can be traced, there is the oriental Pantheism,<lb id="d39873e35021" n="11"/>
                    the Dualism, the Tina (the primary emanation from the Ineffable Supreme), with his<lb id="d39873e35023" n="12"/>
                    twelve Dii Consentes, half male &amp; half female, (twelve was the sacred &amp; dominant num-<lb id="d39873e35025" n="13"/>
                        ber, not in <placeName ref="#GettyID:7014986">Egypt<!--//Start of metadata enrichment--><addName type="display">Egypt</addName><addName>Egypt</addName><addName>Egypt, ancient</addName><addName>Aegyptus</addName><addName>Aigyptos</addName><addName>Hwt-ka-Ptah</addName><addName>Kem</addName><addName>Kemi</addName><addName>Kermit</addName><addName>Kemet</addName><addName>Kmt</addName><addName>Ancient Egyptian</addName><!--//End of metadata enrichment--></placeName> &amp; <placeName ref="#GettyID:7024113">Etruria<!--//Start of metadata enrichment--><addName type="display">Etruria</addName><addName>Etruria</addName><addName>Rashna</addName><addName>Rasna</addName><addName>Tuscia</addName><!--//End of metadata enrichment--></placeName> alone, but in <placeName ref="#GettyID:7033030">Palestine</placeName>, in <placeName ref="#GettyID:1000004">Asia Minor<!--//Start of metadata enrichment--><addName type="display">Asia</addName><addName>Asia</addName><addName>Asie</addName><addName>Asien</addName><addName>Azië</addName><addName>Asian</addName><!--//End of metadata enrichment--></placeName>, &amp; other parts of the<lb id="d39873e35040" n="14"/>
                        East,) the <persName ref="#CerlID:cnp00589422" key="#PND:118800574">Cupra<!--//Start of metadata enrichment--><addName type="display">Juno</addName><addName>Cupra</addName><addName>Pronuba</addName><!--//End of metadata enrichment--></persName> or the <persName ref="#CerlID:cnp00589422" key="#PND:118800574">Juno<!--//Start of metadata enrichment--><addName type="display">Juno</addName><addName>Cupra</addName><addName>Pronuba</addName><!--//End of metadata enrichment--></persName>; the <persName ref="#CerlID:cnp00544188" key="#PND:118986155">Minerva<!--//Start of metadata enrichment--><addName type="display">Minerva</addName><addName>Sospitatrix</addName><!--//End of metadata enrichment--></persName>, the <persName ref="#CerlID:cnp00583168" key="#PND:124874711">Neith<!--//Start of metadata enrichment--><addName type="display">Nut (Göttin)</addName><addName>Neith</addName><!--//End of metadata enrichment--></persName> of <placeName ref="#GettyID:7014986">Egypt<!--//Start of metadata enrichment--><addName type="display">Egypt</addName><addName>Egypt</addName><addName>Egypt, ancient</addName><addName>Aegyptus</addName><addName>Aigyptos</addName><addName>Hwt-ka-Ptah</addName><addName>Kem</addName><addName>Kemi</addName><addName>Kermit</addName><addName>Kemet</addName><addName>Kmt</addName><addName>Ancient Egyptian</addName><!--//End of metadata enrichment--></placeName>, &amp; the <persName ref="#CerlID:cnp00542952" key="#PND:118504851">Athena<!--//Start of metadata enrichment--><addName type="display">Athena</addName><addName>Athene</addName><addName>Pallas Athene</addName><!--//End of metadata enrichment--></persName> of <placeName ref="#GettyID:1000074">Greece<!--//Start of metadata enrichment--><addName type="display">Ellás</addName><addName>Ellás</addName><addName>Ellas</addName><addName>Ellinikí Dimokratía</addName><addName>Elliniki Dimokratia</addName><addName>Elliniki Dhimokratia</addName><addName>Greece</addName><addName>Hellenic Republic</addName><addName>Grèce</addName><addName>République hellénique</addName><addName>Griechenland</addName><addName>Grecia</addName><addName>Griekenland</addName><addName>Grécia</addName><addName>GRC</addName><addName>GR</addName><addName>ISO300</addName><addName>GR00</addName><addName>Kingdom of Greece</addName><addName>Hellas</addName><addName>Greek</addName><addName>Hellenic</addName><!--//End of metadata enrichment--></placeName>;<lb id="d39873e35064" n="15"/>
                        the <persName ref="#CerlID:cnp01303741">Sethlans<!--//Start of metadata enrichment--><addName type="display">Sethlans</addName><!--//End of metadata enrichment--></persName>, the <persName ref="#CerlID:cnp00588165" key="#PND:118770462">Vulcan<!--//Start of metadata enrichment--><addName type="display">Vulcanus</addName><addName>Volcanus</addName><!--//End of metadata enrichment--></persName>, or the <persName ref="#CerlID:cnp00546060" key="#PND:119054221">Pthah<!--//Start of metadata enrichment--><addName type="display">Ptah</addName><!--//End of metadata enrichment--></persName>; still there is nothing which indicates a pe-<lb id="d39873e35076" n="16"/>
                        culiar relationship to <placeName ref="#GettyID:7014986">Egypt<!--//Start of metadata enrichment--><addName type="display">Egypt</addName><addName>Egypt</addName><addName>Egypt, ancient</addName><addName>Aegyptus</addName><addName>Aigyptos</addName><addName>Hwt-ka-Ptah</addName><addName>Kem</addName><addName>Kemi</addName><addName>Kermit</addName><addName>Kemet</addName><addName>Kmt</addName><addName>Ancient Egyptian</addName><!--//End of metadata enrichment--></placeName> than to any other part of the East.</foreign><lb id="d39873e35081" n="17"/></ab></note><note id="d39873e35082" place="end"><ab id="d39873e35083"><foreign xml:lang="en">On the remarkable coincidences in the style of building - the discovery of Egyptian anti-<lb id="d39873e35086" n="18"/>
                    quities in the very oldest sepulchres,- the extraordinary resemblance ot the sepulchres<lb id="d39873e35088" n="19"/>
                        themselves with the necropolis of <placeName ref="#GettyID:7001297">Thebes<!--//Start of metadata enrichment--><addName type="display">Thebes</addName><addName>Thebes</addName><addName>Tebe</addName><addName>Thèbes</addName><addName>Thebae</addName><addName>Thebae Aegypti</addName><addName>Thēvai</addName><addName>Thiva</addName><addName>Theben</addName><addName>Thebai</addName><addName>Thívai</addName><addName>Diospolis Magna</addName><addName>Diospolis</addName><addName>Nowe</addName><addName>Nuwe</addName><addName>No</addName><addName>Wase</addName><addName>Woʻse</addName><addName>Theban</addName><!--//End of metadata enrichment--></placeName> - the apparent analogies between the Etrus-<lb id="d39873e35093" n="20"/>
                    can &amp; the Egyptian mythology, particularly in the ceremonies of the dead - (the <hi rend="underline">Mant<unclear>xx</unclear></hi><lb id="d39873e35099" n="21"/>
                        of <placeName ref="#GettyID:7024113">Etruria<!--//Start of metadata enrichment--><addName type="display">Etruria</addName><addName>Etruria</addName><addName>Rashna</addName><addName>Rasna</addName><addName>Tuscia</addName><!--//End of metadata enrichment--></placeName> answering in his office, as well as closely corresponding in his name, with the<lb id="d39873e35105" n="22"/><hi rend="underline">Amenti</hi> of <placeName ref="#GettyID:7014986">Egypt<!--//Start of metadata enrichment--><addName type="display">Egypt</addName><addName>Egypt</addName><addName>Egypt, ancient</addName><addName>Aegyptus</addName><addName>Aigyptos</addName><addName>Hwt-ka-Ptah</addName><addName>Kem</addName><addName>Kemi</addName><addName>Kermit</addName><addName>Kemet</addName><addName>Kmt</addName><addName>Ancient Egyptian</addName><!--//End of metadata enrichment--></placeName>) - on these grounds <persName ref="#CerlID:cnp00388307" key="#PND:117013110">Signor Micali<!--//Start of metadata enrichment--><addName type="display">Micali, Giuseppe</addName><addName>Giuseppe Micali</addName><addName>Joseph Guiseppe Micali</addName><addName>Josephe Micali</addName><!--//End of metadata enrichment--></persName> does not hesitate to rest his hy-<lb id="d39873e35115" n="23"/>
                        pothesis of the civilazation of <placeName ref="#GettyID:7024113">Etruria<!--//Start of metadata enrichment--><addName type="display">Etruria</addName><addName>Etruria</addName><addName>Rashna</addName><addName>Rasna</addName><addName>Tuscia</addName><!--//End of metadata enrichment--></placeName> by a sacerdotal colony from <placeName ref="#GettyID:7014986">Egypt<!--//Start of metadata enrichment--><addName type="display">Egypt</addName><addName>Egypt</addName><addName>Egypt, ancient</addName><addName>Aegyptus</addName><addName>Aigyptos</addName><addName>Hwt-ka-Ptah</addName><addName>Kem</addName><addName>Kemi</addName><addName>Kermit</addName><addName>Kemet</addName><addName>Kmt</addName><addName>Ancient Egyptian</addName><!--//End of metadata enrichment--></placeName>.</foreign><lb id="d39873e35124" n="24"/></ab></note><note id="d39873e35125" place="end"><ab id="d39873e35126"><foreign xml:lang="en">The characters of the Etruscans resembled the Pelasgic. The Etruscans wrote them from wright to left,<lb id="d39873e35129" n="25"/>
                    &amp; this remained the sacred or hieratic character:</foreign><lb id="d39873e35131" n="26"/><foreign xml:lang="la">"Non Thyrrena retro volventem carmina frustra<lb id="d39873e35134" n="27"/>
                        Iudicia occultae Divum perquirere mentis."-</foreign><lb id="d39873e35136" n="28"/><note id="d39873e35137" place="margin"><ab id="d39873e35138"><foreign xml:lang="en">On the Etrurian Antiquities not a<lb id="d39873e35141" n="29"/>
                        vestige of hieroglyphics is found</foreign><lb id="d39873e35143" n="30"/>
                        Quart. Rev. Sept. 1835.<lb id="d39873e35145" n="31"/></ab></note></ab></note></div></div></body><TEI:pb/></TEI:body></TEI:text></TEI:TEI>